concept_explanation.invariance:
**Generic invariance** — the fundamental rule:

```java
// Class hierarchy: Integer extends Number extends Object
Number n = new Integer(42);  // OK — IS-A relationship

// Generic types are INVARIANT:
List<Number> numbers = new ArrayList<Integer>();  // COMPILE ERROR!
// List<Integer> IS NOT a List<Number>

// Why? Safety:
void add(List<Number> list) { list.add(3.14); }  // legal if allowed
List<Integer> ints = new ArrayList<>();
add(ints);  // would corrupt ints with a Double!
```

**The three options when a type relationship doesn't hold:**
1. Use `List<? extends Number>` — read-only access to a list of Number or subtypes
2. Use `List<? super Integer>` — write-only (safe add) to a list of Integer or supertypes
3. Use `List<Number>` — only accepts exactly List<Number>, nothing else

concept_explanation.unbounded_wildcard:
**Unbounded wildcard `?`** — 'a list of something unknown':

```java
// Accepts List<String>, List<Integer>, List<Object>, List<anything>:
void printSize(List<?> list) {
    System.out.println("Size: " + list.size());  // OK — size() doesn't need T
    for (Object item : list) {                   // OK — can read as Object
        System.out.println(item);
    }
    list.add("hello");  // COMPILE ERROR — can't add to List<?>
}

List<String>  strings = Arrays.asList("Aisha", "Raj");
List<Integer> ints    = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3);
printSize(strings);  // OK
printSize(ints);     // OK
```

**With `?`**: you can READ elements as Object. You CANNOT write (add elements).

**Why no writes?** The compiler doesn't know what type `?` is. It could be `List<String>`. If you add an Integer, that's a bug. So all adds are blocked — even `null` (via `list.add(null)` is technically allowed but unusual).

**Use unbounded `?` when**: you only need container-level operations (size, clear, iteration as Object) and don't care about the element type.

concept_explanation.upper_bounded:
**Upper bounded wildcard `? extends T`** — producer/reading:

```java
// Accepts List<Number>, List<Integer>, List<Double>, List<Long>:
double sumOfList(List<? extends Number> list) {
    double sum = 0;
    for (Number n : list) {      // reads as Number — safe!
        sum += n.doubleValue();
    }
    return sum;
    // list.add(42);  // COMPILE ERROR — can't add to ? extends
}

List<Integer> ints    = Arrays.asList(10, 20, 30);
List<Double>  doubles = Arrays.asList(1.5, 2.5);
System.out.println(sumOfList(ints));    // 60.0
System.out.println(sumOfList(doubles)); // 4.0
```

**`? extends T`**: you can READ elements as T. You CANNOT add elements.

**Why no adds?** The `?` could be `List<Integer>`. If you add a Number (which might be a Double), that's a ClassCastException in the underlying List<Integer>.

**Use `? extends T` when**: you're reading/consuming from the collection — treating it as a producer of T-values.

concept_explanation.lower_bounded:
**Lower bounded wildcard `? super T`** — consumer/writing:

```java
// Accepts List<Integer>, List<Number>, List<Object>:
void addNumbers(List<? super Integer> list) {
    list.add(10);   // OK — Integer satisfies ? super Integer
    list.add(20);   // OK
    // Integer n = list.get(0);  // COMPILE ERROR — can only read as Object
    Object obj = list.get(0);    // OK — read as Object
}

List<Integer> ints    = new ArrayList<>();
List<Number>  numbers = new ArrayList<>();
List<Object>  objects = new ArrayList<>();

addNumbers(ints);    // OK — Integer is ? super Integer
addNumbers(numbers); // OK — Number is ? super Integer
addNumbers(objects); // OK — Object is ? super Integer
// addNumbers(new ArrayList<Double>())  // ERROR — Double is NOT ? super Integer
```

**`? super T`**: you can ADD elements of type T. You can only READ as Object.

**Why only Object reads?** The `?` could be `List<Object>`. When you get an element, you don't know if it's Integer, Number, or Object — safest is Object.

**Use `? super T` when**: you're adding/writing to the collection — treating it as a consumer of T-values.

concept_explanation.pecs_rule:
**PECS — the rule that makes wildcards click:**

**P**roducer **E**xtends, **C**onsumer **S**uper

```java
// PRODUCER — something you READ FROM:
// Use ? extends T
void process(List<? extends Animal> animals) {
    for (Animal a : animals) a.speak();  // READING from animals
}

// CONSUMER — something you WRITE TO:
// Use ? super Cat
void adopt(List<? super Cat> shelter) {
    shelter.add(new Cat());   // WRITING to shelter
    shelter.add(new Kitten()); // OK — Kitten extends Cat
}

// BOTH — reading and writing:
// Use exact type parameter <T>
// OR use two separate: <T> void copy(List<? extends T> source, List<? super T> dest)
```

**The famous Java example** — `Collections.copy()`:
```java
public static <T> void copy(List<? super T> dest, List<? extends T> src) {
    for (T element : src)   // reads from src (? extends T = producer)
        dest.add(element);  // writes to dest (? super T = consumer)
}
```

**Memory trick**: think about the direction of data flow.
- Data flows OUT of the collection → it's a Producer → use `extends`
- Data flows IN to the collection → it's a Consumer → use `super`

concept_explanation.wildcard_vs_type_param:
**Wildcard vs type parameter — when to use each:**

```java
// Use TYPE PARAMETER when:
// - The method uses the type in multiple places (return type, multiple params)
// - You need to enforce a relationship between parameters

public static <T> T getFirst(List<T> list) { return list.get(0); }  // returns T — needs T
public static <T> void swap(List<T> list, int i, int j) { ... }   // needs T internally

// Use WILDCARD when:
// - You only need one occurrence of the type
// - You don't need to name the type

public static void printAll(List<?> list) { ... }          // ? — don't care what type
public static double sum(List<? extends Number> list) { } // ? extends — read as Number

// Multiple wildcards for different types:
public static <T> void copy(List<? super T> dest, List<? extends T> src) { }
// Here T ties dest and src together — needs type parameter for the relationship
```

**Rule of thumb**: if you'd write the same T exactly once, consider using `?` instead. If T appears in the return type or multiple parameters that must agree, use a named type parameter.

concept_explanation.common_wildcard_patterns:
**Common wildcard patterns in daily Java:**

```java
// Print any collection
void print(Collection<?> c) { c.forEach(System.out::println); }

// Sum any numeric collection
double sum(Collection<? extends Number> nums) {
    return nums.stream().mapToDouble(Number::doubleValue).sum();
}

// Add items to a collection of a base type
void addAll(List<? super String> dest, String... items) {
    for (String s : items) dest.add(s);
}

// Process a map with unknown key type
void printValues(Map<?, String> map) {
    map.values().forEach(System.out::println);
}

// Stream-friendly: method accepting List of any Animal subtype
void processAnimals(List<? extends Animal> animals) {
    animals.stream()
        .filter(a -> a.isHungry())
        .forEach(Animal::feed);
}
```

